We’ve encountered a strange issue at our competition. For all of our matches so far, there is a noticeable ~3 second delay between the start of autonomous, and when our robot actually starts moving. Right now, all I can point to is our DS Log.

Q25 Match Log.zip (101.9 KB)

During a match, you can see a ~3 second delay between the DS Auto indicator and the Robot Auto indicator.

The branch we were working off of is here, in the Kettering—Modified-Arm-Code:

GitHub

GitHub - frc1718/2024-BuildSeason-1718: Code for Team 1718's 2024 Robot, Nessie.

Code for Team 1718's 2024 Robot, Nessie. Contribute to frc1718/2024-BuildSeason-1718 development by creating an account on GitHub.

One bit of code we did modify; we noticed this recent thread, which sounds exactly like our issue.

(PathPlanner Initial Lag after Deploying Code)

However, implementing the solution from the last post didn’t appear to fix the issue.

We’ve been seeing a issue I suspect is related. More generically, it seems like we get a brief code lockup/loop overrun the first time SwerveDrivetrain::seedFieldRelaive (docs) is called after Rio boot, whether it’s by Pathplanner at the beginning of auto or whether it’s in teleop bound to a controller button.

Are you seeing the same issue at home? Do you see the same issue if you run auto a second time without rebooting the robot?

We have not investigated it deep enough to determine a root cause, though I have two suspicions:

a. In the CTRE Swerve API, there’s a ReentrantLock on odometry since it’s updated in a separate higher speed thread from the main robot execution. It’s possible we’re waiting a long time on this lock. On the other hand, that odometry update thread is running at 250hz, so you wouldn’t expect anything to be holding onto this lock for very long. This also doesn’t explain why it only happens once after the Rio boots. Additionally, it doesn’t look like Spectrum is using the CTRE swerve code.

b. PathPlanner Initial Lag after Deploying Code - #6 by Peter_Johnson. This provides a better explanation for why the issue only occurs once after boot. I can’t tell what classes wouldn’t be loaded already though, since almost all of the same code paths would be exercised just by the odometry thread starting up and running.

Our code is here. This one has definitely stumped us, as we do our best to try to stick to tried and true architectures (basically bone stock WPILib Commands with the CTRE Swerve API) and assumed an issue like this would be seen by more people.

I don’t remember seeing this issue at our practice field, but it’s possible that it just wasn’t that noticeable. Unfortunately, we’ve been unable to recreate it while tethered in the pits or the practice field at the competition. We’ve only seen it on the field, but I really don’t think it’s a field issue, because our trip time and packet loss appear pretty low.

I noticed the lock in seedFieldRelative, but I would expect the issue to happen each time we enter autonomous. We’re going to try some more to recreate the issue, so hopefully I can report back with some sort of update.

It could be. Loading your auto routines before you start autonomous is a good idea.

I’m also hearing a lot of people complaining about Java’s lazy classloading. This essentially means that the first time you run a particular piece of code may be much slower. The way to avoid this is to “warm up” that routine. I note that PathPlanner has recently added a warm up command.
